##"Rush to register" patent of Wuhan Virus Institute: "Unusual Operation" under epidemic situation?

Micro Signal deeptechchina

Function description DeepTech is a full-chain content, service, data and investment and financing platform focusing on the emerging technology industrialization, and is committed to building a global network of scientific and technological innovation cooperation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A message from the Chinese Academy of Sciences went viral.

China has made significant progress in anti COVID-19 drug screening, the report, which was published on the virus institute's website on Feb. 4, said, researchers at the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the PLA Academy of Military Science found that Remdesivir effectively suppressed the 2019-nCoV infection at the cellular level, it filed a Chinese invention patent (against the use of the 2019 COVID-19) on January 21 and will enter major countries around the world through the PCT (patent cooperation agreement) route.

It is worth noting that domestic researchers filed a patent on January 21, while the first case of new coronavirus pneumonia in the United States was confirmed on January 20, local time. Researchers at the Virus Institute and the PLA Academy of Military Science have their eye on when it comes to preparing cells for research.

The study was published in the Journal Cell Research in a Letter to the Editor.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fig. From Cell Research

The development was supposed to be good news because of the urgency of the outbreak, but the patent filing has attracted a lot of attention. For a time, people have been asking whether the US company Gilead is prepared to help China fight the epidemic, or whether researchers are trying to get Gilead to beg them to give the drug to Chinese patients?

There are many questions, the virus and PLA Academy of Military Science this operation is compliant? What is the international practice? How useful is the patent on the results of the cell test?

Dr. Wang Chenguang, a former professor at Peking Union Medical College who has worked on immunotherapy drug development, told DeepTech that the team's operation was not technically problematic, but only in the context of the current epidemic prevention first, such an operation is open to controversy. Dr. Chen, who has worked in the pharmaceutical industry for multinational companies, said there may be no controversy here, but the patent is not valid either.

A patent for a cell-based experiment

There are more than authors of this cell trial study. The authors are Xiao Gengfu, a researcher at Wuhan Institute of Virology, Zhong Wu, a researcher at the National Center for Emergency Prevention and control of pharmaceutical engineering, and Hu Zhihong, a researcher at Wuhan Institute of Virology. The Co first authors of the paper are Wang Manli of Wuhan Institute of Virology, Cao Ruiyuan of the National Engineering Research Center for Emergency Prevention and control of military medicine, Zhang Leiwei of Wuhan Institute of Virology, and Yang Xinglou. Liu Jia, Xu Mingyue and Shi Zhengli are co authors.

The study evaluated the antiviral effects of several drugs at the cellular level. They tested the cells with different concentrations of 2019-nCoV and administered the drug. Research has shown that Radzivir does not stop the virus from entering the cell, but rather acts as an inhibitor after the virus enters the cell, which is consistent with its Nucleic acid analogue antiviral mechanism.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | antiviral activity of drugs against COVID-19(2019-nCoV) in vitro. (Source: Virus Institute of Chinese Academy of Sciences)

In African Green monkey kidney cells (Vero E6 cells) , the 50% effective concentration EC500.77 uM for 2019-nCoV (micromole per liter) , the choice index SI is greater than 129, which is an indicator of the safe range of drug efficacy. According to the authors, this shows that the drug can effectively inhibit the 2019-nCoV infection at the cellular level, and its role in human remains to be clinically proven.

Remdesivir (GS-5734) is an RNA polymerase inhibitor, a new type of Nucleoside analogue antiviral drug. A clinical trial to treat Ebola virus disease is currently under way in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. The study found that the drug's effects were not limited to filoviruses such as Zaire Ebolavirus, but also inhibited a variety of viruses such as coronaviruses.

In previous reports, vanderbilt University Virologist Mark Denison, Chinese Academy of Engineering Academician, senior Expert Group Member of the National Health Commission Yuen Kwok-yung, Fudan University affiliated Shanghai Municipal Public Health Clinical Center Professor Lu Hongzhou all said that the drug in the anti-new coronavirus application prospects.

Gilead also said it is working with Chinese health authorities to conduct a randomized, controlled trial to determine the safety and efficacy of the treatment of patients infected with 2019-nCoV. The drug has arrived in China.

The study in China was led by Cao Bin, vice president of the China Japan Friendship Hospital and Director of the respiratory and critical care medicine department. It was a three phase, randomized, double blind, placebo controlled trial that included patients with mild to moderate new pneumonia, total sample size 270 cases. The trial will be carried out in the epidemic area of Wuhan. The study is scheduled to end on April 27.

Researchers at the Institute of Virology and the PLA Academy of Military Science say that for the Drug Ridgeville, which is not yet listed in China and has intellectual property barriers, it is in the interest of protecting national interests, in line with international practice, filed a Chinese invention patent (against 2019 COVID-19 uses) on January 21, and will enter major countries around the world through the PCT route. "If foreign companies are interested in contributing to the prevention and control of the epidemic in our country, we have agreed not to claim the rights claimed by the patent for the time being if the country needs it, and we hope to work together with foreign pharmaceutical companies to contribute to the prevention and control of the epidemic. "

Expert interpretation of Drug Research and development

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure | Gilead is working with Chinese health authorities to conduct a randomized, controlled trial to determine the safety and efficacy of the treatment of 2019-nCoV infected patients. (Source: Gilead)

The drug, which was originally developed to fight Zaire Ebolavirus, is a new use for the drug, which was the starting point for a patent filed by researchers at the Virus Institute and the PLA Academy of Military Science. We interviewed Chen Dawei, a former professor at Peking Union Medical College, and Wang Chenguang, a former immunotherapy drug developer at several multinational companies.

First, we asked the experts about the ownership of the patent and the right to apply. Will the way that the virus and the PLA Academy of Military Science Obtained Ridgeville affect their patent application? If Gilead donated, do they have the right to apply for a patent?

In general, pharmaceutical companies welcome research organizations to do some research with their products because the latter can help them discover new drug data, Dr. Chen said. This drug is not necessarily from the company, sometimes the market can also be bought. If you do it yourself, it's a violation.

As for the patent issue, it depends on the agreement between them. A common way to obtain compounds from companies for preclinical trials is through a material transfer agreement (MTA) between the academic center and the company. The right of both parties to apply for a patent will be specified in the agreement. Companies generally require research organizations to explain what they are seeking the compound for and why they are seeking a specific amount, but do not charge a fee. If the research institution is to conduct research that does not potentially conflict or threaten the interests of the company, approval is usually granted.

There are some differences among pharmaceutical companies in the yardstick of patents. For some preclinical studies, some drug companies may allow other institutions to apply for their own patents, but for clinical research, few pharmaceutical companies allow other institutions to apply for their patents.

Dr Wang does not think they need to rely on Gilead's donation. Because Ridgeway's molecular structure was already known, it was easy to synthesize, and there were no technical hurdles. Whether or not the drug is patented has nothing to do with its origin, and whether or not it was donated by Gilead does not affect its patent application.

Another question is how effective is a patent under the condition that the public is most concerned about a drug that has not yet been tested in a clinical trial and relies solely on the results of a cell trial?

To this problem, Dr. Chen Dawei thinks this is patentable. But it should have little impact on the eventual new clinical application. If Gilead wants to do this kind of clinical research, it could use cell studies from the PLA Academy of Military Science and the University of California, San Diego. In other words, the latter does not hold a clinical patent on the drug.

In addition, he said, except Gilead, other organizations or individuals do not have the right to use the drug in clinical trials, and the drug is not yet on the market. If other institutions collaborate with Gilead on clinical trials (which is common, and in many cases require some funding from the drug company) , the Drug Company has the initiative and the partner research institution can not own the patent.

There may not be a compliance issue, but the patent itself is not valid. It is common for research institutions other than Gilead to use unapproved drugs in animal or cell experiments.

But Dr. Wang is more critical, arguing that patents that claim a therapeutic effect based only on cell test results are weak if they do not provide clinical trial results, you're not well protected. But once the virus has applied for the patent, no other person or organization can apply for the patent.

Of course, the virus in this patent if there are future applications, it can not bypass Gilead, after all, the molecular structure is someone else's patent. It's just that Gilead would have to go to the virus lab and the PLA Academy of Military Science to use the patent in China. Because their patent protects the ridgeway APP.

The Virus Institute and the PLA Academy of Military Science have the upper hand here, since the new coronaviruses are most prevalent in China, so they have a natural advantage. So they were able to snap up the patent. They also applied for a patent cooperation agreement (PCT) , which allowed them to apply for patents in various countries and regions around the world.

In general, there is nothing technically or legally wrong with this practice, but at the moment, such behavior is controversial and is no longer simply a matter of intellectual property protection.

There is also the very real question of what Patents Gilead, which already holds a patent on the drug's molecular structure, can apply to researchers at the Virus Institute and the PLA Academy of Military Science, and how Gilead might react? Dr. Wang gave this answer:

They can apply for a patent for a combination drug or for other uses of the drug. If Gilead did not patent RIDGEVILLE's use of the new coronavirus, others could. It wouldn't be a problem if we patented a combination of Ridgeville. As long as Gilead is getting treatment for the new coronavirus, the same rules apply.

Of course, the new coronaviruses may be gone like the SARS virus, so the patent is nothing to Gilead.

Finally, DeepTech asked Dr. Donald Trump about a previous report that U.S. President Donald Trump had asked Gilead to disclose the molecular structure of Ridgeway. He thinks this is actually a media misreading. Gilead's disclosure of Ridgeville's molecular structure, whether it donates drugs, whether it is licensed, is a corporate activity, and Donald Trump has no right to interfere.

Wuhan Virus Research Institute Patent or difficult to be authorized

Gilead has already patented the structure of the compound and its use as a treatment for coronaviruses, according to available data.

The patent for the compound has been granted, given as CN103052631B, the patent for the use is pending, and the patent for the use is given as CN108348526A, which describes the use of Radzivir for all coronaviruses, that is to say, gilead has applied for a patent for the use of the hammer in a type of nail called the coronavirus.

Things seemed to get complicated for a while. In response, DeepTech contacted Li Chunxuan, a partner of Li Xuan, a law firm, to explain. He said new patents from the Wuhan Institute of Virology would need to prove their novel, creative and practical use of the new coronavirus.

And according to the definition of novelty in a patent review guide for a chemical product, a utility invention of a new product is naturally novel because the product is new.

For medical inventions involving chemical products, the novelty review should consider the following:

(a) whether the new use is substantially different from the previously known use. Inventions that are essentially of the same use but in different forms are not novel.

(2) whether the new use is directly disclosed by the mechanism of action and pharmacological action of the previously known use. The application directly equivalent to the original mechanism of action or pharmacological action is not novel.

(III) whether the new use is a top-up concept of the previously known use. Known inferior uses can destroy the novelty of superior uses.

(4) whether the characteristics related to the use, such as the object of administration, the mode of administration, the way of administration, the dosage and the time interval, etc. , have a restrictive effect on the pharmaceutical process. The use can not be novel simply because of the distinguishing characteristics that are present in the process of administering the drug.

Given the existing public information is difficult to prove the difference between the Wuhan Virus Research Institute's Program and Gilead Program, Li Chunxuan believes that the Wuhan Virus Research Institute's Patent Application is more difficult to be authorized.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Source: Wuhan Virus Research Institute)

HERE IS QA:

DEEPTECH: What is the complete process of the Wuhan Institute of Virology from the patent rush to the license?

Li Chunxuan: There is no so-called "rush to register" , the patent is an application-approval system.

Before this, there were two main systems of patent application in the world. One was the pre-invention system in a few countries, such as the United States. That is, more than two applicants applied for patents on the same invention and creation respectively, and the patent right was granted to the first inventor. The other is the other country's first application system, who filed the application first, the patent to whom. The American AIA Invention Act was later changed to the inventor first application system. A patent application needs to be approved before it can be granted, and eventually the same patent application will be granted to the first applicant.

There's no rush on the patent. Patent licensing focuses on three aspects, novelty, creativity and practicality, and is now mainly concerned with novelty and creativity, as long as a technical solution has not been published before the application, there is the possibility of being licensed. In addition to these three attributes, there are other text-based licensing conditions that vary from country to country, but the criteria for review are generally convergent.

In general, the average time between the filing of a patent for an invention and the granting of a license is about three years. A pharmaceutical patent is a typical invention patent. It usually lasts about three years.

DEEPTECH: From a patent perspective, is what Wuhan is doing legal?

Li Chunxuan: What Wuhan is doing is completely legal. Setting aside the licensing issue, even if this patent is granted, it still has a lot of implementation problems.

First, the treatment of patients is not affected by patent law, which does not protect the treatment and diagnosis of diseases.

The United States has already filed a patent for a drug in China, and the Wuhan Institute of Virology Must Obtain Permission from the United States to use it to treat the new coronavirus pneumonia, or risk infringement.

Just because an American patentee doesn't have a cease-and-desist right now, doesn't mean he doesn't have rights. The right is always in the hands of the American patent holder.

The drug was originally used to treat Zaire Ebolavirus, and the Wuhan Virus Research Institute has discovered a new use for it, that is, it can be used to treat a new coronavirus, and then apply for a related patent, theoretically, if the patent is granted, in future, U. S. companies will need approval from Wuhan if they want to use the drug to treat the new coronavirus.

With or without an outbreak, such cases are actually quite common.

For example, a has made something that can only be used for a because of R & D costs or other constraints, and now B has done some research and found that it can be used for B. A can only enjoy the benefits of use a, not the benefits of use B. This is why second use patents are allowed by law.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fig. Remdesivir? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? ? 

DEEPTECH: Now that the information shows that the drug is effective against the new coronavirus only in vitro cells, don't need more experiments to patent it?

Li Chunxuan: the patent application is to protect the technical program, it requires that the technical program is theoretically feasible. In addition, at present, in the practice of drug patent application, the application documents must be supported by experimental data, otherwise it can not be authorized, which is the text of patent application requirements.

The problem is that, whether or not the patent is granted, the Wuhan Institute of Virology has already proposed and published the technical proposal by various parties, no one else will be able to patent the use of the drug as a new coronavirus treatment. When technical solutions are made public, others can not be empowered without novelty and creativity.

DEEPTECH: How will the Wuhan Institute of Virology's Patent Application Affect Gilead?

Li Chunxuan: Gilead can not apply for a second-use patent for the drug, but according to the information now available, Gilead's claim already includes related uses and is not affected by the Wuhan Virus Institute.

DEEPTECH: The Wuhan Institute of Virology is considered by some to be tantamount to taking the work of others as their own.

Li Chunxuan: First of all, Wuhan Institute of Pharmaceutical Research is not illegal, reason is reason, law is law. Even reasonable is normal, because we do not know what Wuhan to pay for this Labor.
